production to the propellant.The melting point of uranium<br>
is 1800 celcius.The melting point of beryllium is<br>
2500 celcius. Here we will use 10% pure U 235<br>
as the reacter fuel . 10 %  Heu can not generate an <br>
atomic explosion because its neutron multiplier factor is not high enough to do this when it goes critical<br>
<br>
<br>
 Therefore we need only 500 kilograms of 10% Leu to achieve 2.5 atomic critical masses   in the core.because the u 235 fuel rods are encased completely inside hollow beryllium metal cylindrical  sheaths .<br>
<br>
 The 15 kiloton atomic blast that destroyed hiroshima was generated by about 2.5 critical masses of 80% Heu.<br>
<br>
<br>
  These hollow cylindrical  metal sheaths are wielded between <br>
the two ends of  a 3 inch thick  cylindrical steel containment vessel.<br>
<br>
 There are also 5 control rods made of  boron metal<br>
which are placed inside of 5 cylindrical passages, and <br>
operated by electric motors.<br>
<br>
 The atomic core  is made of 5 100 kilogram Uranium rods  which are placed inside of 5 100 kilogram berylium sheaths in a hexaganal honey comb pattern.<br>
<br>
 Around each of the 5 fuel rods  are 5 beyllium metal<br>
hollow tubes through which the liquid hydrogen propellant is pumped by compressed nitrogen gas pressure feed pumps.<br>
The hydrogen goes through the top of the tubes and comes<br>
out the bottom of them to enter a converging-diverging<br>
45  degree beryllium delaval rocket nozzle.<br>
<br>
 There is a double containment vessel made of two<br>
3 inch thick steel walls around the atomic reactor core.<br>
This double wall  steel radiation shield is enough to block all the nuclear radiation that would be released from a high yield nuclear bomb explosion.<br>
 <br>
 There are hollow beryllium tubes between these two walls wich carry liquid hydrogen around the atomic reactor core to cool it and then into the core of the reactor to be heated up to about 2500 celcius (4500 farenheit) .The reactor core<br>
sustained temperature after it is cooled by the propellant will<br>
be about 1250 Celcius which is below the melting temperature of the uranium. Even if all the uranium melted it will be safely<br>
held within the berylium  fuel rod sheaths which have a meting point of 2500 Celcius.<br>
 <br>
<br>
U238 is a  alpha particle emitter<br>
which undergoes an alpha decay process.<br>
Its radiation can be stopped by a sheet of paper.<br>
<br>
 Uranium 235 atoms occasionly undergo spontaneous <br>
fission and emmitt neutrons however.And there are of course <br>
the fission fragment isotopes, which are either alpha or beta particle emitters whose radiation can be blocked by a mere sheet of paper.These isotopes can not harm you unless they get inside of your body, which will never occurr in a properly<br>
selected nuclear rocket launch site such as the desert.<br>
Only the neutrons can harm you from outside your body .<br>
<br>
 This is what manner of radiological threat there is from 500 kilograms of uranium for example . The so called radiological threat from a nuclear rocket argued by yales is in reality virtually non existant. It is an illogical  figment of his imagination and of  his antinuclear paranoi.<br>
<br>
<br>
  It takes 1 watt of heat to raise the temperature of 1<br>
gram of propellant by one degree celcius.1 watt of heat =<br>
1 joule of heat energy. It takes 1000 grams to make 1 kilogram of mass. Here we assume the propellant for ntr is liquid hydrogen. It then takes 5000 watts of heat energy to<br>
heat 1 gram  of hydrogen to 2500 celcius. 1 kilogram of<br>
h2 needs 5 megawatts to reach this temperature in the <br>
reactor core. It takes 50 megawatts to heat 10 <br>
kilograms of h2 to 2500 C. <br>
<br>
 By the rocket eqautions:<br>
1 kilogram  of h2 expelled per second  at 9000 meters per sec <br>
(Si =900 seconds) will generate about 56,000 pounds <br>
of thrust (for a nerva class engine) and 10 kilograms<br>
per second will generate about 560,000 pounds of thrust<br>
for a phoebus class nuclear engine,<br>
<br>
So let us make a reusable delta winged 500,000 pound ntr <br>
spaceplane with a 4/1 mass ratio and one phoebus<br>
 class 560,000 pound thrust nuclear thermal  engine, <br>
which will also have a space shuttle style heat shield on it.<br>
There is 375,000 pounds of liquid hydrogen stored in a<br>
75,000 pound tank and we will assume a maximium mass for the nuclear engine of 10,000 kilograms (22000 pounds .<br>
This leaves 78,000 pounds for the rest of the vehicle<br>
including the delta wings, heat shield, pilots cabin,<br>
and perhaps a 20,000 kilogram payload to where ever.Any questions, comments, discussion  about this superior nuclear driven and possible : orbital or lunar space shuttle?<br>
Tim<br>
,<br>
By the rocket equation V final  = Ve * ln mi/mf at burnout<br>
which is 12,476 meters per second. So with this nuclear<br>
space plane you can achieve 1 stage to leo , or 1 stage to lunar orbit. You can also achieve a 1 stage undecelerated<br>
flyby of mars ,venus, jupiter, or saturn with this space plane<br>
<br>
<br>
