 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/umauk2.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 14<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/10/02 10:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Here is a plan for a nuclear thermal rocket space launch</span><hr size=1> yales: Ah, now we're talkin'.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  I understand your design quite well, and as stated, is doomed to failure.  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It's DOOMED!  DOOMED I TELL YA!!!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
I think not.  <br>
<br>
You said: <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  You have disregarded approxmately 3 gigawatts of radiant energy per engine, resulting in containment failure. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Ah, you attack the weakest part of the design, curse you!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
You are correct, keeping the silica lightbulb intact is critical.  Keeping it cool is actually the smallest problem as I see it, since we can readily make it a triple walled vessel and vent hydrogen gas between the layers.  If you will direct your attention to my original post, I detail a possible gas cooling cycle which should address the thermal issues quite handily.<br>
<br>
No, in my mind, the worst issues with the lightbulb is vibration, erosion, and pressure differences between the inside and the outside.    Vibration is always a problem in rocket design, and with heavy computer modeling it should be easy to control with tuning, damping, and monitoring.<br>
<br>
 Erosion may be more difficult, but using micropores in the inner and outer surfaces should allow enough of the coolant gas to bleed through to form a &quot;cushion.&quot;  This is actually a trick I believe could be used extensively throughout the thruster to protect the fragile physical materials from the extreme conditions, basically allowing the inside of the engine to &quot;ablate away&quot; a cool gas layer while the core is hot.<br>
Heck, all the gas gets to several thousand kelvin and goes out the nozzle eventually, how it is injected matters not.<br>
<br>
Pressure differences.  Now THIS is a tough one.  If turbulence happens either inside or outside the lightbulb, the bulb could be shattered.  Fortunately, gas flow and behavior inside combustion chambers is very well understood, and turbulence is easily designed away.  The presence of the passively triggered boron shotgun scram mechanism is specifically aimed at this risk, among others.   Unwanted turbulence in any rocket engine usually results in Bad Things, so it is a well understood issue.   Using three walled lightbulbs helps here, if any layer shatters we should have time to fast scram the reaction and vacuum the core gas into the fuel sorage vault.<br>
<br>
A more insidious issue of pressure differential is if the chamber pressure either inside the lightbulb or outside of it simply &quot;drifts&quot; out of sync.  This issue could be addressed by a passive rupture valve.  If the pressure outside gets too high, the rupture valve lets some of the reaction mass into the buffer layer. If the pressure inside gets too high, the rupture valve allows some of the buffer gas to vent.  Now this is BAD, as we now have a hole in our containment!  We immediately activate the gas jet turbulence scram system to remove criticality and cool the fissile mass, and then we trigger the vacuum scram sytem and suck the fissile material into the fuel vault, where the boron moderator takes the fissile material into deep non-criticality.<br>
<br>
So, do you still stand by your assertion that I have &quot;disregarded&quot; the thermal loads?  Or do you care to ask me to &quot;sweat the details&quot; some more?  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  That is irrelevant tho, Particular failure mechanisims are unimportantant. Common mode failures, software bugs, LH2 system failures, etc. all can lead to loss of the vehicle, and total catastrophe. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Oh, no!  Not &quot;common mode failures!&quot;  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
The massive redundancy and multiple systems to perform similar tasks <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  in different ways </b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> are a powerful defense against such common mode failures.  I would be more worried about unforseen interactions between systems, since there are so many of them.   I am willing to take that level of interoperability risk to drive down the possibility of a common mode failure.<br>
<br>
Software bugs.  Okay, the boron shotgun passive scram device is PASSIVE.  No computers, no sensors, heck, it doesn't even use any power.  It's basically a gas canister loaded with boron pellets with a weak window into the lightbulb.  Sure, EVERYTHING else can go wrong, but when the core tries to run away from you, the shotgun breaks and kills the core.  There is a reason why I put on TWO extra thrusters, I fully expect one or more to scram on almost every launch., especially early in the design cycle.  <br>
<br>
LH2 system failures are a worry, which is why I used THREE turbopumps on EVERY thruster, running at less than 90 percent of rated power.  Even if a turbopump dies, the booster flies on.  <br>
<br>
As for problems in the piping and plumbing, be serious.  The turbopump is by FAR the most heavily stressed part of the LH2 system.  <br>
<br>
The problem which killed the Challenger was a long term jet of rocket propellant blasting against the side of the storage tank.  To my knowledge, there have been very few cracks and leaks in flight LH2 plumbing, and I address even that small concern by putting aside HUGE amounts of mass for these systems.  The LH2 plumbing in this booster will be very heavily constructed compared to that in the Space Shuttle, for instance.  Thicker gauge pipes, heavier and stronger welds, as few welds as possible due to computer designed castings, etc.  Remember, all design parameters here are massively overbuilt compared to a traditional launcher because with nuclear power, we have mass to throw away on safety.<br>
<br>
But, let's assume all of those protections fail, and we have a catastrophic failure anyway.  Let's assume it is of a violence similar to the Challenger disaster.<br>
<br>
Since the nuclear cores are designed to survive their operating conditions, they should EASILY survive the detonation of the LH2 tankage.  Remember, the crew of Challenger was probably alive until impact, and human beings are not nearly as sturdy as that lightbulb.  Heck, the SRB's flew out of the fireball and kept on going!  This is NOT delicate machinery.  As a further note, the LH2 in this booster is only reaction mass, there is no onboard oxygen to combust with.  If the explosion happens at altitude the &quot;explosion&quot; will be positively gentle.<br>
<br>
It would be a matter of course to have contingencies progammed into the flight computers.  If there is a total loss of the vehicle in a Challenger style explosion, there would be ample state changes to signal what has happened.    <br>
<br>
First, the boron shotgun is immediately fired, and then the vacuum scram device is also triggered.  The vacuum scram is not QUITE a passive device, since a valve has to be powered, but the driving force to extract the fissile mass is a vacuum inside the fuel storage system.  I expect the vacuum scram to extract the UF6 / boron / helium from the lightbulb in less than a second.  The fuel mass is now stored in thickwalled aluminum/boron tubing, which is assembled in some dense arrangement, probably looking very similar to a radiator.<br>
<br>
The fuel storage system is a very robust system, and is buried deep in the structure of the booster, as close to the thrust structure as is feasible.  It would be easy to design it to survive intact nearly ANY conceivable re-entry, since if we are in this level of disater mitigation model, I would be perfectly willing to sacrifice the rest of the vehicle to ensure the fuel vaults make it to the ground unbroken.<br>
<br>
No total catastrophe.  A very bad thing, but no total catastrophe.   <br>
<br>
BUT, let's assume for the sake of assuming that ALL of the defenses fail.  The entire vehicle, all 1,600,000 pounds of it, reinforced, redundant, armored, is reduced to dust by some unimaginable event.  A head-on collision with a meteorite the size of a car would do it, so I can't just roll my eyes and proclaim it to be impossible.  Of course the odds of getting hit by a meteorite during your ascent phase is pretty low, but it is non-zero.  So lets assume it happens. <br>
<br>
There is a total release of ALL the fuel on the vehicle.<br>
<br>
This is STILL not as bad as the Ivy Mike nuclear test, which released at least 50 percent more fallout into the air than even this unlikely event, and there was no catastrophe.  We know these risks and we can manage them.   Radiation is not some kind of magical poison.  It is part of nature, actually.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  You seem to be adopting the same &quot;Unsinkable Titanic&quot; mindset that the nuclear industry did. Your defense-in-depth is anything but. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I dunno, so far I seem to have addressed every concern you have.  That defense in depth I postulate has defenses against every contingency you have come up with, and even the magical &quot;it evaporates because radiation is evil&quot; scenario is STILL manageable.   Maybe you need to &quot;sweat the details&quot; a little harder.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
I have said it before, I will say it again: This design is not without risk.  But it is easily safe enough.  Especially considering the performance.<br>
<br>
This booster could be used to capture asteroids.  It could fly up and bring back the ENTIRE space station in one trip.  And the Space Telescope on the same trip.  Easily.  It could launch a bonafide spaceship to Mars, with crew and all its supplies and fuel, in one trip.  Heck, with a small rebuild, it could FLY to Mars and back.  Or the Moon.  It could deliver a helium 3 refinery to the Moon in one shot.  Etc.  Etc.  Etc.<br>
<br>
There is PLENTY of stuff for this machine to do.  It is worth a little risk, in my mind.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Oh, as a note, I really expected you to attack the fuel life-cycle!  That is the most vulnerable point of the design, isn't it?  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Go ahead, ask me about the fuel life-cycle, it is interesting.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 790<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/11/02 7:15 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   A lesson... The Explosion of the Ariane 5</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>   The Explosion of the Ariane 5<br>
<br>
On June 4, 1996 an unmanned Ariane 5 rocket launched by the European Space Agency exploded just forty seconds after its lift-off from Kourou, French Guiana.  The rocket was on its first voyage, after a decade of development costing $7 billion. The destroyed rocket and its cargo were valued at $500 million. A board of inquiry investigated the causes of the explosion and in two weeks issued a report. It turned out that the cause of the failure was a software error in the inertial reference system. Specifically a 64 bit floating point number relating to the horizontal velocity of the rocket with respect to the platform was converted to a 16 bit signed integer. The number was larger than 32,767, the largest integer storeable in a 16 bit signed integer, and thus the conversion failed. <br>
<br>
The following paragraphs are extracted from the report of the Inquiry Board. An interesting article on the accident and its implications by James Gleick appeared in The New York Times Magazine of 1 December 1996. The CNN article reporting the explosion, from which the above graphics were taken, is also available. <br>
<br>
On 4 June 1996, the maiden flight of the Ariane 5 launcher ended in a failure. Only about 40 seconds after initiation of the flight sequence, at an altitude of about 3700 m, the launcher veered off its flight path, broke up and exploded. <br>
<br>
The failure of the Ariane 501 was caused by the complete loss of guidance and attitude information 37 seconds after start of the main engine ignition sequence (30 seconds after lift-off). This loss of information was due to specification and design errors in the software of the inertial reference system. <br>
<br>
The internal SRI* software exception was caused during execution of a data conversion from 64-bit floating point to 16-bit signed integer value. The floating point number which was converted had a value greater than what could be represented by a 16-bit signed integer. <br>
<br>
*SRI stands for Systme de Rfrence Inertielle or Inertial Reference System.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.ima.umn.edu/~arnold/disasters/ariane.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
much more later...<br>
