<br>
Ah, the ultraviolet probem!  Yes, I am aware of this issue.  Even in the 70's it was seen to be readily correctable by seeding a layer of the buffer gas inside the lightbulb with silica dust.  This silica dust absorbs the UV, promptly melts, and re-radiates those 3 gigawatts lower down on the frequency scale, where the lightbulb has higher transmissivity.  This silica vapor layer could be considered as a &quot;4th lightbulb&quot; inside the three physical layers.<br>
<br>
Keep swingin'!  You're doing good so far!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
Also as a note, there will be a considerable amount of development work to get this engine to work, it is very possible different and better ways of solving the transmissivity issue will be found.  Given the huge amount of work done on glass due to the fiber optic boom (which occurred after work on this design was stopped) I suspect far more elegant solutions will be found.<br>
