 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 795<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/11/02 12:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: A lesson... The Explosion of the Ariane 5</span><hr size=1> You need to account for the thickness of the &quot;dust&quot; layer. Your engine is operating in the range of 30+ gigawatts. This is many multiples of any previous analysis.<br>
<br>
Describe the thickness, absorption, and re-emission characteristics of a layer sufficient to deal with the energies, the effect of this layer on the transmission of other frequencies, and the interaction of this mechanism on the other moving and flowing components, in a lightbulb device generating 10's of gigawatts in an engine a few meters in diameter.<br>
<br>
